[start section id="20112"]

#1 Synchronous adenocarcinoma of the colon (pT4, N1, M0)
#2 Autosomal recessive MYH-associated polyposis syndrome
I was able to discuss with Mr. Ortiz and his wife today the pre-operative evaluation, the findings on pathology at the time of diagnosis, as well as the results of his Medical Genetics testing.  I was also able to discuss the case with Dr. Bowman today, who confirmed that he feels the more distal cancerous lesion that was removed was indeed a sigmoid and not a rectal lesion.
In this setting, I feel that we should treat with Mr. Ortiz as having stage III disease given two different T4 lesions and one positive lymph node.  On this note, we would utilize chemotherapy in the form of FOLFOX every two-weeks times 12 cycles.  Given the more distal lesion was felt sigmoid in nature, we do not feel that radiation therapy would be indicated in this case.
This was all discussed at length with Mr. Ortiz and his wife.  They do plan to receive their chemotherapy care closer to home, and actually have an appointment with Dr. Boivin in Casselton already scheduled, and we informed them that they would be able to discuss the route, schedule of administration, and toxicities of the chemotherapy regimen to administered more fully at that time.
It is unclear exactly how Mr. Ortiz will respond to chemotherapy as patients with these MYH mutations are quite rare, and it is unknown what the efficacy of chemotherapy in the adjuvant setting is in these patients.  Regardless, we would recommend it, and I have expressed to Mr. Ortiz that we would be happy to see him back at GCGH at any point during his care for further evaluation.  At this time, he is unclear whether he would like to get imaging studies done at GCGH, in Casselton, or both.  I informed him that I would not schedule any follow-up at this time and leave him to have that conversation with Dr. Boivin in Casselton.  He and his wife expressed understanding and many informed questions were answered.
I have discussed this case at length with Dr. Kane who also saw and examined the patient.  Please see his note for further details.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

